title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A further primitive query-former is the union or intersection of a certain <fr:em>family</fr:em> of queries indexed in the <fr:em>results</fr:em> of a fixed query. These are written as follows:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/union-fam{q}{qfam}
\query/isect-fam{q}{qfam}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>In the above, <fr:code>q</fr:code> is a query expression and <fr:code>qfam</fr:code> is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00YF.xml"
addr="jms-00YF"
title="First-class functions and lazy arguments"><fr:em>first-class function</fr:em></fr:link> that takes an address and returns a query expression. There are a couple built-in instantiations of <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/union-fam]]></fr:code> and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/isect-fam]]></fr:code> for the specific case where <fr:code>qfam</fr:code> is a family of <fr:em>relational</fr:em> queries; for example:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/union-fam-rel{q}{mode}{polarity}{rel}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>is equivalent to the following more verbose code:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/union-fam{q}{
 \fun[x]{
  \query/rel{mode}{pol}{\x}
 }
}]]></fr:pre><fr:tree
